Things are really greening up here SW Wisconsin! This is the first time I've offered this stunning Sea Green Swallowtai and yes, that is a single, puny morel mushroom I found this morning!!
Swallowtails have tails on the end of their hindwings, which help them escape predators in the wild. In the hopes that a bird will grab onto their tail, which they don’t need in order to fly, instead of some other part of their wing or body which are more critical for survival, the butterfly has a chance to get away unharmed. The bird “swallows the tail” instead of the butterfly, hence the name “swallowtail”.

🦋The Monarch and the Mimic🦋
This one of a kind necklace features one half a Monarch butterfly and it's mimic, the Viceroy!

Monarchs are toxic to invertebrates, so any mammal or bird that might wish to take a bite into a Monarch will quickly regret the decision. However, it has been recently discovered that Viceroys are, in fact, toxic as well, having evolved a different kind of toxin than Monarchs. So this is actually called Müllerian co-mimicry and not the Batesian mimicry as previously thought. Müllerian mimicry is when two or more species evolve similar appearances when both toxicity and/or foul taste, so that a lesser toll is taken on each species by predators who are still learning to avoid that appearance. By looking almost the same and both being toxic partners, the two species both benefit from each other!

If only Luna moths were the size of a small dog it'd be the perfect pet😂
The Luna moth, Actias luna, is a beautiful nocturnal insect with eye spots on its pale green wings and signature long tails that act as a lure to predators like birds and bats. If they break off the fluttering wing tails in the attack, the moth will survive another night!
They live for about one week, during this time they don't feed as they do not have functioning mouth parts, relying solely on the energy reserves built up during the caterpillar stage!

A few weeks ago there were dragonflies everywhere and I was given this nice specimen by a friend who found it near their driveway. I learned it was a Green Darner, named because it resembles a darning needle.. from back in the day when people would take the time to fix holes in their clothes and socks with a darning needle! Also Green darners have another secret: some of them migrate. Large flocks have been seen along mountain ridges and shorelines in both autumn and spring. Like monarch butterflies, this migration is a multi-generational affair; the dragonflies that journey south will not be the ones that come back north next spring. Unlike monarchs, though, green darners don’t seem to gravitate to a specific area. We know little about the mechanisms or specifics about darner migration, so this is an area where some amazing facts will likely come out over the next few years.

There's been some really beautiful Wisconsin winter sunsets lately which of course inspired this Sunset moth piece! 
The brilliant colors of the Madagascan Sunset Moth (Urania ripheus) warn predators of it's toxicity, and will draw attention to this stunning piece of framed insect art. Unlike most other moths, this beautiful symbol of faith and determination is not nocturnal, but flies by day.
